{"title_page": "Easton, Suffolk", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2017}}\n[[File:Easton - Church of All Saints.jpg|thumb|[[All Saints Church, Easton|Church of All Saints, Easton]]]]\n'''Easton''' in England is situated on the [[River Deben]] around three miles south of [[Framlingham]] and is the former estate village of Easton Park, one-time seat of the [[Duke of Hamilton]]. The population of the parish at the 2011 Census was 331.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11123045&c=IP13+0EA&d=16&e=62&g=6466932&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=0&s=1442228359289&enc=1|title=Parish population 2011|accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[William Douglas-Hamilton, 12th Duke of Hamilton]], died without male issue in 1895 and the title passed to his fourth cousin, who became [[Alfred Douglas-Hamilton, 13th Duke of Hamilton]]. Although the Dukedom and estates had passed, a large share of the Hamilton lands and properties, including Easton park, went to Lady Mary, the 12th Duke and Duchess's only child.\n\nAfter [[World War I]] the British government imposed colossal taxes on the rich to help defray the cost of the war. Faced with these taxes and with the cost of restoring Easton Park from it use as a Red Cross Hospital during the war, the late-12th Duke's daughter the Duchess of Montrose and her husband [[James Graham, 6th Duke of Montrose]], decided to sell the estate.\n\nThe land was divided into 137 lots and sold by auction in 1919. The sale attracted a great deal of attention and raised \u00a358,000 (\u00a34.6 million today) but Easton park itself (often referred to as 'the Mansion') and its 150-acre parkland remained unsold. It was sold privately for \u00a311,278 (\u00a3900,000 today) and the parkland was transferred to Martley Hall. With very little land the Mansion's fate was sealed and in December 1924 demolition began. Some of the artifacts were removed and incorporated into Martley Hall and other local houses.\n\nEaston is still home to the pack of hunting hounds established by the 12th Duke in the 19th century. The pack of [[harrier (dog)|harrier]]s was established and funded entirely by the duke, much to the delight of the local landowners and farmers. Following his death in 1895, the committee received the Dowager Duchess's permission to name the pack the 'Hamilton Hounds' in his memory. Since the succession of the 13th Duke and the consequent split of Easton away from the Hamilton estate, the connection between the family and the hunt has waned. The hunt is now called the Easton Harriers and is still an integral part of the village, and shows good sport in the local area.\n\nEaston is also the home of Easton Farm Park, a farming museum with a selection of rare breeds and depicting other countryside related activities.\n\nEaston is also the home of Little Legs and The Guv'nor. No paparazzi please! \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*http://easton.onesuffolk.net/village-info/history-part-1/\n*[http://suffolk.activeboard.com/index.spark?aBID=119775&p=3&topicID=15702770 Suffolk Punch Horse]\n\n{{Commons category|Easton, Suffolk|Easton}}\n\n{{Coord|52.179|1.337|type:city_region:GB-SFK|display=title}}\n\n{{East Suffolk}}\n\n{{Suffolk}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Suffolk]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Suffolk]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=April 2017}}\n[[File:Easton - Church of All Saints.jpg|thumb|[[All Saints Church, Easton|Church of All Saints, Easton]]]]\n'''Easton''' in England is situated on the [[River Deben]] around three miles south of [[Framlingham]] and is the former estate village of Easton Park, one-time seat of the [[Duke of Hamilton]]. The population of the parish at the 2011 Census was 331.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11123045&c=IP13+0EA&d=16&e=62&g=6466932&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&o=362&m=0&r=0&s=1442228359289&enc=1|title=Parish population 2011|accessdate=14 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[William Douglas-Hamilton, 12th Duke of Hamilton]], died without male issue in 1895 and the title passed to his fourth cousin, who became [[Alfred Douglas-Hamilton, 13th Duke of Hamilton]]. Although the Dukedom and estates had passed, a large share of the Hamilton lands and properties, including Easton park, went to Lady Mary, the 12th Duke and Duchess's only child.\n\nAfter [[World War I]] the British government imposed colossal taxes on the rich to help defray the cost of the war. Faced with these taxes and with the cost of restoring Easton Park from it use as a Red Cross Hospital during the war, the late-12th Duke's daughter the Duchess of Montrose and her husband [[James Graham, 6th Duke of Montrose]], decided to sell the estate.\n\nThe land was divided into 137 lots and sold by auction in 1919. The sale attracted a great deal of attention and raised \u00a358,000 (\u00a34.6 million today) but Easton park itself (often referred to as 'the Mansion') and its 150-acre parkland remained unsold. It was sold privately for \u00a311,278 (\u00a3900,000 today) and the parkland was transferred to Martley Hall. With very little land the Mansion's fate was sealed and in December 1924 demolition began. Some of the artifacts were removed and incorporated into Martley Hall and other local houses.\n\nEaston is still home to the pack of hunting hounds established by the 12th Duke in the 19th century. The pack of [[harrier (dog)|harrier]]s was established and funded entirely by the duke, much to the delight of the local landowners and farmers. Following his death in 1895, the committee received the Dowager Duchess's permission to name the pack the 'Hamilton Hounds' in his memory. Since the succession of the 13th Duke and the consequent split of Easton away from the Hamilton estate, the connection between the family and the hunt has waned. The hunt is now called the Easton Harriers and is still an integral part of the village, and shows good sport in the local area.\n\nEaston is also the home of Easton Farm Park, a farming museum with a selection of rare breeds and depicting other countryside related activities.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*http://easton.onesuffolk.net/village-info/history-part-1/\n*[http://suffolk.activeboard.com/index.spark?aBID=119775&p=3&topicID=15702770 Suffolk Punch Horse]\n\n{{Commons category|Easton, Suffolk|Easton}}\n\n{{Coord|52.179|1.337|type:city_region:GB-SFK|display=title}}\n\n{{East Suffolk}}\n\n{{Suffolk}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Suffolk]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Suffolk]]\n", "name_user": "5.67.48.82", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Easton,_Suffolk"}
{"title_page": "National Games of China", "text_new": "{{Infobox sporting event organization\n|name         = National Games of the People's Republic of China<br>\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u5168\u56fd\u8fd0\u52a8\u4f1a\n|image        = AllChinaGamesFlag.svg\n|caption      =\n|image2       = \n|size2        = \n|caption2     = \n|abbreviation = National Games of the PRC; All China Games \n|motto        = \n|formation    = 1959\n|recurrence   = 4 years\n|last         = \n|purpose      = Sports for elite athletes in [[People's Republic of China|China]]\n|headquarters = \n|leader_title = \n|leader_name  = \n|website      ={{url|en.olympic.cn/games/national}} \n|remarks      =\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|showflag=stp\n|s=\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u5168\u56fd\u8fd0\u52a8\u4f1a\n|t=\u4e2d\u83ef\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b\u5168\u570b\u904b\u52d5\u6703\n|p=Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 R\u00e9nm\u00edn G\u00f2ngh\u00e9gu\u00f3 Qu\u00e1ngu\u00f3 Y\u00f9nd\u00f2nghu\u00ec\n|w=Chunghua Jenmin Kunghekuo Ch'\u00fcankuo Y\u00fcntunghui\n}}\n\nThe '''National Games of the People's Republic of China''', sometimes known as the '''All China Games''' (though not to be confused with the [[All-China Games]]), is the premier sports event in [[China]] at national level. It is usually held once every four years, most recently in August 2017, when the [[2017 National Games of China|13th National Games of China]] took place in [[Tianjin]]. \n\nThe forerunner of the Games was the '''Chinese National Games''', first held in 1910 during the [[Qing dynasty]]. This tournament ran until 1948 and the competition was relaunched under its current name in 1959, following the [[history of the People's Republic of China|formation of the People's Republic of China]].<ref>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/nc/chn.htm Chinese National Games]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2009-10-24.</ref> On the other hand, the original Chinese National Games continued to be held by the [[Taiwan|Republic of China]] which is now based in [[geography of Taiwan|Taiwan]].<ref>[https://zh.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E4%B8%AD%E5%8D%8E%E6%B0%91%E5%9B%BD%E5%85%A8%E5%9B%BD%E8%BF%90%E5%8A%A8%E4%BC%9A \u4e2d\u534e\u6c11\u56fd\u5168\u56fd\u8fd0\u52a8\u4f1a] {{zh icon}}</ref>\n\n== List of the National Games of China ==\n{{location map+|China|float=center|width=500|caption=Host cities of the games through 2021|places=\n{{Location map~|China||position=|lat=41.817651|long=123.431472|label='''[[Liaoning|2013]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=left|lat=39.909395|long=116.413938|label='''[[Beijing|1959, 1965, 1975, 1979, 1993]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=right|lat=39.099266|long=117.200983|label='''[[Tianjin|2017]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=right|lat=36.664033|long=117.120000|label='''[[Shandong|2009]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=|lat=34.265|long=108.954|label='''[[Shaanxi|2021]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=|lat=32.076702|long=118.796877|label='''[[Jiangsu|2005]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=right|lat=31.244211|long=121.473701|label='''[[Shanghai|1983, 1997]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=|lat=23.145803|long=113.277283|label='''[[Guangdong|1987, 2001]]'''}}\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Games\n!Hosts\n!Dates\n!Teams\n!Athletes\n!Sports\n!Events\n!Ref\n|-\n|align=center|[[1959 National Games of China|I]]\n|[[Beijing|Beijing Municipality]]\n|13 September\u20133 October 1959\n|align=right|29\n|align=right|10,658\n|align=right|42\n|align=right|384\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[1965 National Games of China|II]]\n|[[Beijing|Beijing Municipality]]\n|11\u201328 September 1965\n|align=right|29\n|align=right|5,014\n|align=right|23\n|align=right|300\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[1975 National Games of China|III]]\n|[[Beijing|Beijing Municipality]]\n|12\u201328 September 1975\n|align=right|31\n|align=right|12,497\n|align=right|42\n|align=right|310\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[1979 National Games of China|IV]]\n|[[Beijing|Beijing Municipality]]\n|15\u201330 September 1979\n|align=right|31\n|align=right|15,189\n|align=right|36\n|align=right|469\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[1983 National Games of China|V]]\n|[[Shanghai|Shanghai Municipality]]\n|18 September\u20131 October 1983\n|align=right|31\n|align=right|8,943\n|align=right|26\n|align=right|277\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[1987 National Games of China|VI]]\n|[[Guangdong|Guangdong Province]]\n|20 November\u20135 December 1987\n|align=right|37\n|align=right|7,228\n|align=right|44\n|align=right|343\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[1993 National Games of China|VII]]\n|[[Beijing|Beijing Municipality]]\n|4\u201315 September 1993\n|align=right|45\n|align=right|7,481\n|align=right|43\n|align=right|374\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[1997 National Games of China|VIII]]\n|[[Shanghai|Shanghai Municipality]]\n|12\u201324 October 1997\n|align=right|45\n|align=right|7,943\n|align=right|28\n|align=right|319\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[2001 National Games of China|IX]]\n|[[Guangdong|Guangdong Province]]\n|11\u201325 November 2001\n|align=right|45\n|align=right|8,608\n|align=right|30\n|align=right|345\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[2005 National Games of China|X]]\n|[[Jiangsu|Jiangsu Province]]\n|12\u201323 October 2005\n|align=right|42\n|align=right|9,986\n|align=right|32\n|align=right|483\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[2009 National Games of China|XI]]\n|[[Shandong|Shandong Province]]\n|16\u201328 October 2009\n|align=right|46\n|align=right|10,991\n|align=right|33\n|align=right|551\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[2013 National Games of China|XII]]\n|[[Liaoning|Liaoning Province]]\n|31 August\u201312 September 2013\n|align=right|39\n|align=right|9,770\n|align=right|31\n|align=right|350\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[2017 National Games of China|XIII]]\n|[[Tianjin|Tianjin Municipality]]\n|27 August\u20138 September 2017\n|align=right|38\n|align=right|8,478\n|align=right|33\n|align=right|417\n|\n|-\n|align=center|[[2021 National Games of China|XIV]]\n|[[Shaanxi|Shaanxi Province]]\n|2021\n|align=right|\n|align=right|\n|align=right|\n|align=right|\n|\n|}\n\n== Statistics ==\n{{main article|Statistics of the National Games of China}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[All-China Games]]\n* [[Asian Games]]\n* [[China National Youth Games]]\n* [[East Asian Games]]\n* [[Football at the National Games of China]]\n* [[National Peasants' Games]]\n* [[Olympic Games]]\n* [[Sport in China]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://en.olympic.cn/games/national/list.html Partial list from Chinese Olympic Committee]\n\n{{Chinese National Games}}\n{{International multi-sport events}}\n\n[[Category:National multi-sport events|China]]\n[[Category:Multi-sport events in China]]\n[[Category:National Games of China|*]]\n[[Category:1910 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1910]]\n[[Category:1959 establishments in China]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1959]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sporting event organization\n|name         = National Games of the People's Republic of China<br>\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u5168\u56fd\u8fd0\u52a8\u4f1a\n|image        = AllChinaGamesFlag.svg\n|caption      =\n|image2       = \n|size2        = \n|caption2     = \n|abbreviation = National Games of the PRC; All China Games \n|motto        = \n|formation    = 1959\n|recurrence   = 4 years\n|last         = \n|purpose      = Sports for elite athletes in [[People's Republic of China|China]]\n|headquarters = \n|leader_title = \n|leader_name  = \n|website      ={{url|en.olympic.cn/games/national}} \n|remarks      =\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|showflag=stp\n|s=\u4e2d\u534e\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u56fd\u5168\u56fd\u8fd0\u52a8\u4f1a\n|t=\u4e2d\u83ef\u4eba\u6c11\u5171\u548c\u570b\u5168\u570b\u904b\u52d5\u6703\n|p=Zh\u014dnghu\u00e1 R\u00e9nm\u00edn G\u00f2ngh\u00e9gu\u00f3 Qu\u00e1ngu\u00f3 Y\u00f9nd\u00f2nghu\u00ec\n|w=Chunghua Jenmin Kunghekuo Ch'\u00fcankuo Y\u00fcntunghui\n}}\n\nThe '''National Games of the People's Republic of China''', sometimes known as the '''All China Games''' (though not to be confused with the [[All-China Games]]), is the premier sports event in [[China]] at national level. It is usually held once every four years, most recently in August 2017, when the [[2017 National Games of China|13th National Games of China]] took place in [[Tianjin]]. \n\nThe forerunner of the Games was the '''Chinese National Games''', first held in 1910 during the [[Qing Dynasty]]. This ran until 1948 and the competition was relaunched under its current name in 1959, following the [[History of the People's Republic of China|formation of the People's Republic of China]].<ref>[http://www.gbrathletics.com/nc/chn.htm Chinese National Games]. GBR Athletics. Retrieved on 2009-10-24.</ref> It's unknown if the Chinese National Games continued by the [[Taiwan|Republic of China]] which is now currently based in Taiwan.\n\n== List of the National Games of China ==\n{{location map+|China|float=center|width=500|caption=Host cities of the games through 2021|places=\n{{Location map~|China||position=|lat=41.817651|long=123.431472|label='''[[Liaoning|2013]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=left|lat=39.909395|long=116.413938|label='''[[Beijing|1959, 1965, 1975, 1979, 1993]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=right|lat=39.099266|long=117.200983|label='''[[Tianjin|2017]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=right|lat=36.664033|long=117.120000|label='''[[Shandong|2009]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=|lat=34.265|long=108.954|label='''[[Shaanxi|2021]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=|lat=32.076702|long=118.796877|label='''[[Jiangsu|2005]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=right|lat=31.244211|long=121.473701|label='''[[Shanghai|1983, 1997]]'''}}\n{{Location map~|China||position=|lat=23.145803|long=113.277283|label='''[[Guangdong|1987, 2001]]'''}}\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Games\n!Hosts\n!Dates\n!Teams\n!Athletes\n!Sports\n!Events\n!Ref\n|-\n|align=center|[[1959 National Games of China|I]]\n|[[Beijing|Beijing Muni