cessdate= August 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=tie090921>{{cite web | first =  Drew | last = Meekins | authorlink= Drew Meekins |author2=Sarah S. Brannen | url = http://web.icenetwork.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090921&content_id=7074614&vkey=ice_news | title = The Inside Edge with Sarah and Drew \u2013 Sept. 21 | date = September 21, 2009 | accessdate = November 3, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=usfs120410>{{cite news | url = http://web.icenetwork.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120410&content_id=28327696&vkey=ice_pressrelease | title = 2010 Olympians Evora, Ladwig end partnership | work = [[U.S. Figure Skating]] | publisher = Ice Network | date = April 10, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=9900usn>{{cite web | url = http://www.usfigureskating.org/content/events/199900/uschamps/novice-pairsfree.htm | title = 2000 State Farm U.S. Figure Skating Championships Novice Pairs Final Standings| publisher = [[U.S. Figure Skating]] | accessdate = November 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=0001usn>{{cite web | url= http://www.usfigureskating.org/content/events/200001/uschamps/novice/novpairs-free.htm | title = 2001 State Farm U.S. Figure Skating Championships \u2013 Novice Pairs | publisher = [[U.S. Figure Skating]] | accessdate = November 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=mh100216>{{cite news | url = http://www.miamiherald.com/2010/02/16/1482034/chinese-pair-in-front.html | title = Figure skating gold goes to Chinese pair | accessdate = April 30, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=0809aac>{{cite web | url = http://www.usfigureskating.org/content/AthletesAdvisoryTree.pdf | title = U.S. Figure Skating Athletes Advisory Committee 2008\u201309 Permanent Committee | format= PDF | publisher = [[U.S. Figure Skating]] | accessdate = November 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=aacl>{{cite web | url = http://www.usfigureskating.org/Story.asp?cat=7&id=826 | title = Athletes Advisory Committee Leadership | publisher = [[U.S. Figure Skating]] | accessdate = November 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=in120504>{{cite news | url = http://web.icenetwork.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120504&content_id=30367476&vkey=ice_news | title = Ladwig searches for new beginning with Davis | first = Lynn | last = Rutherford | work = Ice Network | date = 2012-05-04 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=usfs130207>{{cite news | url = http://www.usfsa.org/Story.asp?id=48971&type=media | title = Lindsay Davis and Mark Ladwig End Partnership | work = [[U.S. Figure Skating]] | date = February 7, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=IN140703>{{cite news |url= http://web.icenetwork.com/news/2014/07/03/82717466 |title= The Inside Edge: Skaters debut new programs |first= Sarah S. | last = Brannen |first2= Drew |last2= Meekins |work= [[U.S. Figure Skating|IceNetwork]] |date= July 3, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mark Ladwig}}\n* {{isu name | id=00054271 | name= Lindsay Davis / Mark Ladwig }}\n* {{isu name | id=00007159 | name= Amanda Evora / Mark Ladwig }}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.evora-ladwig.com/ |date=* |title=Official site of Evora/Ladwig }}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.davisladwig.com/ |date=* |title=Official site of Davis/Ladwig }}\n* {{USOPC profile|LA/Mark-Ladwig}}\n\n{{NavigationGoldenSpinChampionsFigureSkatingPairs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ladwig, Mark}}\n[[Category:American male pair skaters]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Fargo, North Dakota]]\n[[Category:University of Delaware people]]\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Figure skaters at the 2010 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic figure skaters of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox figure skater\n| name = Mark Ladwig\n| image = Amanda EVORA Mark LADWIG Skate America 2009.jpg\n| caption = Evora and Ladwig in 2009.\n| country = United States\n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1980|5|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Fargo, North Dakota]]\n| hometown = \n| residence = \n| height = {{height|ft=5|in=10}}\n| partner =\n| formerpartner = [[Lindsay Davis (figure skater)|Lindsay Davis]], [[Amanda Evora]], Kesley Sollom, Keri Lynn Blakinger\n| formercoach = [[Lyndon Johnston]], Allison Smith, [[Jim Peterson (figure skater)|Jim Peterson]], Kerry Leitch, [[Ron Ludington]], Dawn Franklin\n| formerchoreographer = Cindy Stuart, [[Jim Peterson (figure skater)|Jim Peterson]]\n| skating club = Red River Valley FSC\n| beganskating = 1985\n| retired =\n| worldranking =\n| pbrankings = \n| combined total = 171.92\n| combined date = [[2010 Winter Olympics]]\n| SP score = 57.86\n| SP date = [[2010 Winter Olympics]]\n| FS score = 114.06\n| FS date = [[2010 Winter Olympics]]\n}}\n\n'''Mark Ladwig''' (born May 6, 1980) is an American [[pair skater]]. He is best known for his partnership with [[Amanda Evora]], with whom he competed at the [[2010 Winter Olympics]], placing tenth. They won bronze at an ISU Grand Prix event, the [[2010 Cup of Russia]], and two [[United States Figure Skating Championships|U.S. national]] silver medals. He later skated with [[Lindsay Davis (figure skater)|Lindsay Davis]] for one season.\n\n==Personal life==\nMark Ladwig was born in [[Fargo, North Dakota]] to Carol and John, a medical technician and a doctor respectively, and grew up in [[Moorhead, Minnesota]] with two siblings, Todd and Erin.<ref name=USFS-AEML/> He married his wife, Janet, in August 2006.<ref name=bio1112/> A boy named Holden Everett was born September 13, 2009.<ref name=tie090921/> A second son, Felix Rye Ladwig, was born July 1, 2014.<ref name=IN140703/>\n\n==Career==\nLadwig skated with Kelsey Sollom until 1999 in [[Moorhead, Minnesota]] and then with Keri Blakinger while at the [[University of Delaware Figure Skating Club]] in [[Newark, Delaware]].<ref name=9900usn/><ref name=0001usn/> He volunteered at the 2002 Winter Olympics and worked in Salt Lake Olympic Square.<ref name=grate/>\n\nIn June 2002, Ladwig began skating with [[Amanda Evora]]. They finished 12th in their debut at the U.S. Championships and fifth at their first ISU Championship, the [[2005 Four Continents Figure Skating Championships|2005 Four Continents]]. In 2007, Ladwig began serving on the [[U.S. Figure Skating]] Athletes Advisory Committee.<ref name=aacl/> He was the pairs vice-chair of the 2008\u201309 Athletes Advisory Committee.<ref name=0809aac/>\n\n2009\u201310 was a breakthrough season for Evora/Ladwig. They took second at the [[2010 United States Figure Skating Championships|U.S Championships]], their best finish at the event, which led to their selection for the US Olympic team. At the [[Figure skating at the 2010 Winter Olympics|2010 Vancouver Olympics]], they beat their previous personal best by a sizable margin, and finished tenth, making them the top US pair at the Olympics.<ref name=mh100216/> They later competed at [[2010 World Figure Skating Championships|Worlds]] for the first time in their career, and finished in ninth place.\n\nDuring 2010\u20132011 season, Evora/Ladwig were assigned to compete at Cup of China where they finished fifth (151.66 pts) and later earned their first Grand Prix medal, a bronze, at Rostelecom Cup, with a season's best of 110.27 and total score of 162.85. Evora/Ladwig repeated at US Nationals earning their second silver medal, and were selected to compete at [[2011 Four Continents Championships|Four Continents]] and [[2011 World Figure Skating Championships|Worlds]]. At Four Continents, Ladwig's left skate heel broke during the short program, but he and Evora were able to resume the program within the allowed three minutes after Canadian [[Rudi Swiegers]] lent his own boot to Ladwig.<ref name=sd110217/> Ladwig was able to repair his skate prior to the free skate,<ref name=taipei/> and the pair went on to finish sixth overall. Evora/Ladwig were noted for their longevity as a pair, which is rare in U.S. pair skating.<ref name=ic051811/> Their partnership ended when Evora retired from competitive skating on April 10, 2012.<ref name=usfs120410/>\n\nLadwig was elected to the USOC AAC in 2012. In May, he announced that he had teamed up with [[Lindsay Davis (figure skater)|Lindsay Davis]].<ref name=in120504/> Davis/Ladwig competed at two [[ISU Grand Prix of Figure Skating|Grand Prix]] events and won the pewter medal at the [[2013 United States Figure Skating Championships|2013 U.S. Championships]]. They confirmed the end of their partnership in February 2013.<ref name=usfs130207/>\n\n==Programs==\n\n=== With Davis ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Season\n! [[Short program (figure skating)|Short program]]\n! [[Free skating]]\n! Exhibition\n|-\n! 2012\u20132013 <br><ref name=bio1213/><ref name=USFS-LDML/>\n|\n* Beethoven's 5 Secrets <br><small> by [[The Piano Guys]] </small>\n|\n* [[Angels & Demons (film)|Angels & Demons]] <br><small> by [[Hans Zimmer]] </small>\n|\n* [[Too Close (Alex Clare song)|Too Close]] <br><small> by [[Alex Clare]] </small>\n|}\n\n=== With Evora ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Season\n! [[Short program (figure skating)|Short program]]\n! [[Free skating]]\n! Exhibition\n|-\n! 2011\u20132012 <br><ref name=USFS-AEML/><ref name=bio1112/><ref name=in120118/>\n|\n* [[The Man I Love (song)|The Man I Love]] <br><small> by [[George Gershwin]] </small>\n|\n* [[Daphnis et Chlo\u00e9]] <br><small> by [[Maurice Ravel]] </small> \n* [[List of compositions by Claude Debussy|Reverie]] <br><small> by [[Claude Debussy]] </small>\n|\n|-\n! 2010\u20132011 <br><ref name=USFS-AEML/><ref name=bio1011/>\n|\n* [[The Mask of Zorro]] <br><small> by [[James Horner]] </small>\n|\n* [[Nessun dorma|Nessun Dorma]] <br><small> by [[Giacomo Puccini]] </small>\n|\n|-\n! 2009\u20132010 <br><ref name=USFS-AEML/><ref name=bio0910/>\n|\n* Portuguese Love Theme <br><small> (from [[Love Actually]]) <br> by [[Craig Armstrong (composer)|Craig Armstrong]] </small>\n|\n* [[Piano Concerto No. 2 (Rachmaninoff)|Piano Concerto No. 2 in C Minor]] <br><small>  by [[Sergei Rachmaninov]] </small>\n|\n|-\n! 2008\u2